{
  "doc_id": "10490",
  "text": "Poly(ADP-ribose) polymerase (PARP) proteins are involved in DNA repair, gene expression regulation, genomic stability and cell death. Human PARP family comprises 17 members, out of which PARP1 is the most abundant and best characterized. Due to its critical role in the repair processes of DNA strand breaks, PARP1 became an important target for drug discovery in cancer therapeutics. Human PARP1 is a 113 kDa protein consisting of three main domains: an N-terminal DNA-binding domain (containing three zinc fingers) [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] , a central automodification domain and a C-terminal catalytic domain [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] .",
